\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2   \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "A common feature of various postnatal stem cells is their close\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                association with blood vessels. Postnatal neural stem cells\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                (NSCs) in the ventricular-subventricular zone originate from\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                fetal radial glia (RG), which possess NSC properties. Here, using\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                live imaging and three-dimensional (3D) electron microscopy, we\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                investigated how RG convert into postnatal NSCs and characterized\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                the fine 3D morphology of the ventricular-subventricular zone. We\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                found that preterm birth disrupts RG-endothelial cell\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                interactions during this transformation, impairing both the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                structure and stemness of adult NSCs. These findings underscore\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                the importance of a birth-dependent transformation. Our results\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                indicate that RG fiber transection, which depends on the birth\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                process, and endfoot formation on blood vessels, which depends on\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                birth timing, are both critical steps in the conversion of RG\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                into adult NSCs.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
