\f0\b \cf4 \strokec4 abstract
\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2   \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS) is a multisystemic\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                neurodegenerative disorder, with accumulating evidence indicating\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                metabolic disruptions in the skeletal muscle preceding disease\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                symptoms, rather than them manifesting as a secondary consequence\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                of motor neuron (MN) degeneration. Hence, energy homeostasis is\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                deeply implicated in the complex physiopathology of ALS and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                skeletal muscle has emerged as a key therapeutic target. Here, we\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                describe intrinsic abnormalities in ALS skeletal muscle, both in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                patient-derived muscle cells and in muscle cell lines with\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                genetic knockdown of genes related to familial ALS, such as\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                TARDBP (TDP-43) and FUS. We found a functional impairment of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                myogenesis that parallels defects of glucose oxidation in ALS\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                muscle cells. We identified FOXO1 transcription factor as a key\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                mediator of these metabolic and functional features in ALS\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                muscle, via gene expression profiling and biochemical surveys in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                TDP-43 and FUS-silenced muscle progenitors. Strikingly,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                inhibition of FOXO1 mitigated the impaired myogenesis in both the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                genetically modified and the primary ALS myoblasts. In addition,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                specific in vivo conditional knockdown of TDP-43 or FUS orthologs\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                (TBPH or caz) in Drosophila muscle precursor cells resulted in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                decreased innervation and profound dysfunction of motor nerve\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                terminals and neuromuscular synapses, accompanied by motor\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                abnormalities and reduced lifespan. Remarkably, these phenotypes\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                were partially corrected by foxo inhibition, bolstering the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                potential pharmacological management of muscle intrinsic\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                abnormalities associated with ALS. The findings demonstrate an\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                intrinsic muscle dysfunction in ALS, which can be modulated by\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                targeting FOXO factors, paving the way for novel therapeutic\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                approaches that focus on the skeletal muscle as complementary\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                target tissue.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
