\cf4 \strokec4                cortex (EC). This region of the brain is a highly interconnected\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                integrative hub for sensory and spatial information; it also has\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                a key role in episodic memory formation and is the main source of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                cortical hippocampal inputs1-4. The human EC continues to develop\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                during childhood5, but neurogenesis and neuronal migration to the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                EC are widely considered to be complete by birth. Here we show\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                that the human temporal lobe contains many young neurons\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                migrating into the postnatal EC and adjacent regions, with a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                large tangential stream persisting until the age of around one\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                year and radial dispersal continuing until around two to three\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                years of age. By contrast, we found no equivalent postnatal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                migration in rhesus macaques (Macaca mulatta). Immunostaining and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                single-nucleus RNA sequencing of ganglionic eminence germinal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                zones, the EC stream and the postnatal EC revealed that most\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                migrating cells in the EC stream are derived from the caudal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                ganglionic eminence and become LAMP5+RELN+ inhibitory\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                interneurons. These late-arriving interneurons could continue to\cf2 \strokec2 \
