\f0\b \cf4 \strokec4 abstract
\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "In adult lizards, new neurons are generated from neural stem cells\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               in the ventricular zone of the lateral ventricles. These new\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neurons migrate and integrate into the main telencephalic\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               subdivisions. In this work we have studied adult neurogenesis in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the lizard Podarcis liolepis (formerly Podarcis hispanica) by\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               administering [3H]-thymidine and bromodeoxyuridine as\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               proliferation markers and euthanizing the animals at different\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               survival times to determine the identity of progenitor cells and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               to study their lineage derivatives. After short survival times,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               only type B cells are labeled, suggesting that they are neural\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               stem cells. Three days after administration, some type A cells are\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               labeled, corresponding to recently formed neuroblasts. Type A\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               cells migrate to their final destinations, where they\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               differentiate into mature neurons and integrate into functional\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               circuits. Our results after long survival periods suggest that, in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               addition to actively dividing type B cells, there is also a type B\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               subpopulation with low proliferative activity. We also found that\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               new neurons incorporated into the olfactory bulb are generated\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               both in situ, in the walls of the anterior extension of the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               lateral ventricle of the olfactory bulbs, but also at more caudal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               levels, most likely in anterior levels of the sulcus\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               ventralis/terminalis. These cells follow a tangential migration\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               toward the olfactory bulbs where they integrate. We hypothesized\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               that at least part of the newly generated neurons would undergo a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               specialization process over time. In support of this prediction,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               we found two neuronal populations in the cellular layer of the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               medial cortex, which we named type I and II neurons. At\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               intermediate survival times (1 month) only type II neurons were\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               labeled with [3H]-thymidine, while at longer survival times (3, 6,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               or 12 months) both type I and type II neurons were labeled. This\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               study sheds light on the ultrastructural characteristics of the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               ventricular zone of P. liolepis as a neurogenic niche, and adds to\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               our knowledge of the processes whereby newly generated neurons in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the adult brain migrate and integrate into their final\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               destinations.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
