\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2   \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "Tyramide signal amplification (or catalyzed-reporter deposition)\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                is an analyte-dependent reporter enzyme method that enhances the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                detection sensitivity of any given antigen by catalyzing the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                deposit of labeled tyramide that is covalently bound near the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                target molecule, providing high-density signal. Current methods\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                allow identification of any protein or RNA using antibodies or\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                probes, respectively. This technique has also been validated for\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                electron microscopy detection by either DAB or for\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                gold-conjugated streptavidin staining. Both techniques present\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                several limitations, DAB staining hampers the ultrastructure of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                the sample since it precipitates all over the cell. Streptavidin,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                on the other hand, requires a strong permeabilization protocol\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                which also compromises sample integrity. Hereby, we present a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                methodology which uses TSA in combination with immunogold\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                labeling to improve the detection sensitivity for antigens that\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                cannot be detected by conventional immunogold methods, or whose\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                label is weak compared to background noise. As a proof of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                concept, we show the effectiveness of this technique for\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                detecting difficult antigens expressed in the central nervous\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                system such as NG2, PDGFRa, or BCAS1.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
