\cf4 \strokec4               recovery of the brain after injury. However, the delivery of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               sufficient neuroblasts to distant injured sites is a major\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               challenge because of the limited number of scaffold cells that are\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               available to guide neuroblast migration. To address this issue, we\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               have developed an amphiphilic peptide [(RADA)3-(RADG)]\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               (mRADA)-tagged N-cadherin extracellular domain (Ncad-mRADA), which\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               can remain in mRADA hydrogels and be injected into deep brain\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               tissue to facilitate neuroblast migration. Migrating neuroblasts\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               directly contacted the fiber-like Ncad-mRADA hydrogel and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               efficiently migrated toward an injured site in the striatum, a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               deep brain area. Furthermore, application of Ncad-mRADA to\cf2 \strokec2 \
