\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "Austrolebias annual fishes exhibit cell proliferation and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neurogenesis throughout life. They withstand extreme environmental\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               changes as their habitat dries out, pressuring nervous system to\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               adapt. Their visual system is challenged to adjust as the water\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               becomes turbid. Therefore, this study focused on how change in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               photic environment can lead to an increased cell proliferation in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the retina. We administered 5-chloro-2\uc0\u8242 - deoxyuridine (CldU) and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               5-iodo-2\uc0\u8242 -deoxyuridine (IdU) at different temporal windows to\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               detect cell proliferation in natural light and permanent darkness.\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               Stem/progenitor cells were recognized as IdU+/CldU + nuclei\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               co-labeled with Sox2, Pax6 or BLBP found in the ciliary marginal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               zone (CMZ). The expression pattern of BLBP + glial cells and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               ultrastructural analysis indicates that CMZ has different cell\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               progenitors. In darkness, the number of dividing cells\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               significantly increased, compared to light conditions.\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               Surprisingly, CMZ IdU+/CldU + cell number was similar under light\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               and darkness, suggesting a stable pool of stem/progenitor cells\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               possibly responsible for retinal growth. Therefore, darkness\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               stimulated cell progenitors outside the CMZ, where M\'fcller glia\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               play a crucial role to generate rod precursors and other cell\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               types that might integrate rod-dependent circuits to allow\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               darkness adaptation. Thus, the Austrolebias fish retina shows\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               great plasticity, with cell proliferation rates significantly\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               higher than that of brain visual areas.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
