\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "Even after birth, neuronal production continues in the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               ventricular-subventricular zone (V-SVZ) and hippocampus in many\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               mammals. The immature new neurons (``neuroblasts'') migrate and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               then mature at their final destination. In humans, neuroblast\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               production and migration toward the neocortex and the olfactory\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               bulb (OB) occur actively only for a few months after birth and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               then sharply decline with age. However, the precise spatiotemporal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               profiles and fates of postnatally born neurons remain unclear due\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               to methodological limitations. We previously found that common\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               marmosets, small nonhuman primates, share many features of V-SVZ\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               organization with humans. Here, using marmosets injected with\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               thymidine analogue(s) during various postnatal periods, we\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               demonstrated spatiotemporal changes in neurogenesis during\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               development. V-SVZ progenitor proliferation and neuroblast\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               migration toward the OB and neocortex sharply decreased by 4\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               months, most strikingly in a V-SVZ subregion from which\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neuroblasts migrated toward the neocortex. Postnatally born\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neurons matured within a few months in the OB and hippocampus but\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               remained immature until 6 months in the neocortex. While\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neurogenic activity was sustained for a month after birth, the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               distribution and/or differentiation diversity was more restricted\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               in 1-month-born cells than in the neonatal-born population. These\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               findings shed light on distinctive features of postnatal\cf2 \strokec2 \
