\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "The leucine-rich glioma inactivated (LGI) gene subfamily contains\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               four highly conserved members (LGI1, 2, 3 and 4), which have been\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               described in human, mouse and other mammalians. Although their\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               main roles remain unknown, LGI1 gene mutations have been found in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               human partial temporal lobe epilepsy. Moreover, previous studies\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               showed that the products of these genes exert their function in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the nervous system. The anatomical distribution of these gene\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               transcripts in the brain might give some insight to elucidate\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               their possible function. In this study, the pattern of expression\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               of the four LGI genes was assessed in the brain of C57BL/6J adult\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               mice by in situ hybridization. We found that the LGI1 transcript\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               is mainly expressed in the dentate gyrus and CA3 field of the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               hippocampus. LGI2 and LGI4 genes, which showed a similar pattern\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               of distribution with minor differences, were mostly expressed in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the medial septal area, thalamic reticular nucleus and substantia\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               nigra pars compacta. LGI3-expressing cells were distributed\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               widespread, but were more consistently observed in the hippocampal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               formation, thalamic and hypothalamic nuclei, substantia nigra and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               reticular formation. In summary, LGI1 gene expression is very\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               restricted to intrahippocampal circuitry, which might be related\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               to its involvement in temporal lobe epilepsy. The patterns of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               expression of LGI2 and LGI4 genes are very similar and their\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               distribution in the vertical limb of the diagonal band and in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               putative hippocampal interneurons suggests that the function of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               these genes might be related to the generation of hippocampal\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               theta rhythm. Finally, LGI3 gene widespread expression in the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               brain suggests that its transcripts might be involved in a common\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               cellular process present in different neuronal types.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
