\f0\b \cf4 \strokec4 abstract
\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "In mammals, ventricular walls of the developing brain maintain a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neurogenic niche, in which radial glial cells act as neural stem\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               cells (NSCs) and generate new neurons in the embryo. In the adult\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               brain, the neurogenic niche is maintained in the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               ventricular-subventricular zone (V-SVZ) of the lateral wall of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               lateral ventricles and the hippocampal dentate gyrus. In the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neonatal V-SVZ, radial glial cells transform into astrocytic\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               postnatal NSCs and multiciliated ependymal cells. On the other\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               hand, in zebrafish, radial glial cells continue to cover the\cf2 \strokec2 \
