\f0\b \cf4 \strokec4 abstract
\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "Ochratoxin A (OTA), a mycotoxin that was discovered as a secondary\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               metabolite of the fungal species Aspergillus and Penicillium, is a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               common contaminant in food and animal feed. This mycotoxin has\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               been described as teratogenic, carcinogenic, genotoxic,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               immunotoxic and has been proven a potent neurotoxin. Other authors\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               have previously reported the effects of OTA in different\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               structures of the central nervous system as well as in some\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               neurogenic regions. However, the impact of OTA exposure in the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               subventricular zone (SVZ) has not been assessed yet. To elucidate\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               whether OTA affects neural precursors of the mouse SVZ we\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               investigated, in vitro and in vivo, the effects of OTA exposure on\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the SVZ and on the neural precursors obtained from this neurogenic\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               niche. In this work, we prove the cumulative effect of OTA\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               exposure on proliferation, differentiation and depletion of neural\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               stem cells cultured from the SVZ. In addition, we corroborated\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               these results in vivo by immunohistochemistry and electron\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               microscopy. As a result, we found a significant alteration in the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               proliferation process, which was evidenced by a decrease in the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               number of 5-bromo-2-deoxyuridine-positive cells and glial cells,\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               as well as, a significant decrease in the number of neuroblasts in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the SVZ. To summarize, in this study we demonstrate how OTA could\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               be a threat to the developing and the adult SVZ through its impact\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               in cell viability, proliferation and differentiation in a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               dose-dependent manner.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
