\cf4 \strokec4                of stem cells in the nervous system, and continuously generates\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                new neuronal and glial cells involved in brain regeneration.\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                During aging, the germinal potential of the SVZ suffers a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                widespread decline, but the causes of this turn down are not\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                fully understood. This review provides a compilation of the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                current knowledge about the age-related changes in the NSC\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                population, as well as the fate of the newly generated cells in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                the aged brain. It is known that the neurogenic capacity is\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                clearly disrupted during aging, while the production of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                oligodendroglial cells is not compromised. Interestingly, the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                human brain seems to primarily preserve the ability to produce\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                new oligodendrocytes instead of neurons, which could be related\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                to the development of neurological disorders. Further studies in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4                this matter are required to improve our understanding and the\cf2 \strokec2 \
