\f0\b \cf4 \strokec4 abstract
\f1\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 =\cf2 \strokec2  \cf4 \strokec4 "Oral-facial-digital syndromes (OFDS) gather rare genetic disorders\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               characterised by facial, oral and digital abnormalities associated\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               with a wide range of additional features (polycystic kidney\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               disease, cerebral malformations and several others) to delineate a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               growing list of OFDS subtypes. The most frequent, OFD type I, is\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               caused by a heterozygous mutation in the OFD1 gene encoding a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               centrosomal protein. The wide clinical heterogeneity of OFDS\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               suggests the involvement of other ciliary genes. For 15 years, we\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               have aimed to identify the molecular bases of OFDS. This effort\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               has been greatly helped by the recent development of whole-exome\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               sequencing (WES). Here, we present all our published and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               unpublished results for WES in 24 cases with OFDS. We identified\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               causal variants in five new genes (C2CD3, TMEM107, INTU, KIAA0753\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               and IFT57) and related the clinical spectrum of four genes in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               other ciliopathies (C5orf42, TMEM138, TMEM231 and WDPCP) to OFDS.\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               Mutations were also detected in two genes previously implicated in\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               OFDS. Functional studies revealed the involvement of centriole\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               elongation, transition zone and intraflagellar transport defects\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               in OFDS, thus characterising three ciliary protein modules: the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               complex KIAA0753-FOPNL-OFD1, a regulator of centriole elongation;\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the Meckel-Gruber syndrome module, a major component of the\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               transition zone; and the CPLANE complex necessary for IFT-A\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               assembly. OFDS now appear to be a distinct subgroup of\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               ciliopathies with wide heterogeneity, which makes the initial\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               classification obsolete. A clinical classification restricted to\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               the three frequent/well-delineated subtypes could be proposed, and\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               for patients who do not fit one of these three main subtypes, a\cf2 \strokec2 \
\cf4 \strokec4               further classification could be based on the genotype.",\cf2 \strokec2 \
  
